m the rig’s hyperbaric chamber.</p>\n<p>The diving bell’s lockout mechanism, which was supposed to maintain pressure integrity, failed due to improper handling and faulty maintenance. When the bell was disconnected, the seal between the bell and the chamber was compromised, causing a sudden drop in pressure. This explosive decompression subjected the divers to fatal barotrauma.</p>\n<p>Additional contributing factors included:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Poorly maintained safety valves and pressure gauges.</li>\n<li>Lack of adequate training for personnel involved in decompression procedures.</li>\n<li>Design flaws in the diving bell’s locking and sealing mechanisms.</li>\n<li>Inadequate communication protocols during critical operational phases.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Impact on Offshore Diving and Oil Industry Safety Standards</h2>\n<p>The Byford Dolphin accident served as a grim wake-up call for the offshore oil and gas industry worldwide. Prior to the incident, saturation diving was recognized as inherently risky, but the disaster exposed systemic weaknesses in safety culture and technological safeguards.</p>\n<h3>Changes in Safety Regulations</h3>\n<p>Following a comprehensive inquiry led by Norwegian authorities, several recommendations were implemented to prevent recurrence of similar incidents:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Enhanced certification and regular inspection of diving equipment, especially decompression chambers and diving bells.</li>\n<li>Mandatory training and certification programs for all personnel involved in diving operations, emphasizing emergency protocols and equipment handling.</li>\n<li>Strict adherence to maintenance schedules for critical components, including pressure valves and lockout systems.</li>\n<li>Development of international safety standards and operational guidelines for saturation diving, influencing organizations such as the International Marine Contractors Association (IMCA).</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Technological Improvements Post-Byford Dolphin</h3>\n<p>In the 